Here’s how to install and initialize Mixpanel using the mixpanel-browser package in your React or JavaScript app — step-by-step based on your screenshot:

✅ Step-by-Step Setup (Using npm)

🔹 1. Install the SDK

Go to your terminal (in Replit or VS Code or your project folder), and run:

bash
npm install mixpanel-browser

🔹 2. Initialize Mixpanel

At the top of your App.tsx or index.tsx file, add:

ts
import mixpanel from 'mixpanel-browser';

mixpanel.init("YOUR_PROJECT_TOKEN", {
  debug: true,
  track_pageview: true,
  persistence: "localStorage",
});

🔁 Replace "YOUR_PROJECT_TOKEN" with the one from your dashboard (looks like 321dc03bce... from your earlier image).

🔹 3. Track Events

Anywhere in your code, track user actions like this:

ts
mixpanel.track("User Clicked Chat");
mixpanel.track("Journal Submitted");

You can even add properties:

ts
mixpanel.track("Journal Submitted", {
  wordCount: 245,
  mood: "Anxious",
});

🔹 4. (Optional) Identify Users

If your app has users that log in, you can identify them:

ts
mixpanel.identify(user.id); // unique user ID
mixpanel.people.set({
  $email: user.email,
  $name: user.name,
});

✅ Example Drop-in for App.tsx

tsx
import React from 'react';
import mixpanel from 'mixpanel-browser';

mixpanel.init("321dc03bce...", {
  debug: true,
  track_pageview: true,
  persistence: "localStorage",
});

function App() {
  // optional example of tracking when app mounts
  React.useEffect(() => {
    mixpanel.track("App Loaded");
  }, []);

  return (
    <div className="App">
      {/* your app content */}
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;

Here’s exactly how to identify users in Mixpanel inside your ReflectAI app. This will help you see who’s doing what — not just what’s happening.

✅ 1. Where to Put It

Use this code right after your user logs in or once you have access to the user object.

🧠 2. Code Example with Your Auth Hook

If useAuth() gives you user data, do this:

tsx
import { useAuth } from "@hooks/use-auth"; // already in your code

function App() {
  const { user } = useAuth();

  useEffect(() => {
    if (user) {
      // Identify the user in Mixpanel
      mixpanel.identify(user.id);

      // Optional: Set profile properties
      mixpanel.people.set({
        $name: user.name,
        $email: user.email,
        plan: user.plan || "Free", // adjust based on your setup
      });

      mixpanel.track("User Identified");
    }
  }, [user]);

Make sure your user object includes at least:

  • user.id → unique identifier (e.g. UUID or Mongo ID)

  • user.email

  • user.name (optional)
